    "recap_headline": "",
    "recap_text": "LYNCHBURG, VA. \u2013\nLiberty moved the tying run to second base with one out in the ninth inning, but Missouri State pitcher Tyler Charlton was able to prevent the runner from scoring as the Bears defeated the Flames 4-3 in the CUSA opener for both teams Friday at Worthington Field at Liberty Baseball Field. The loss snaps Liberty's 10-game winning streak.\nThe visiting Bears took their first lead of the contest in the top of the eighth on a two-run home run by catcher Carter Bergman.\nIn the bottom of the ninth, first baseman Riley DeCandio walked and was moved into scoring position at second base on a sacrifice bunt by pinch hitter\nEaston Swofford\n. Missouri State reliever Tyler Charlton then proceeded to hold the runner at second as he recorded the final two outs of the game to close out the victory.\nShortstop\nTanner Marsh\nled the Flames with two hits, an RBI double and a triple, a walk and a run scored.\nLiberty falls to 12-4 overall and 0-1 in CUSA. Missouri State moves to 11-6 overall and 1-0 in conference play.\nBox Score Highlights\nRecords:\nMissouri State (11-6, 1-0 CUSA); Liberty (12-4, 0-1 CUSA)\nLocation:\nLynchburg, Va. (Worthington Field at Liberty Baseball Stadium)\nWP:\nTrent Ashe (1-0) |\nLP:\nJosh Swink\n(1-1) |\nSV:\nTyler Charlton (2)\nScoring Summary\n1\nst\n\u2013 LIBERTY \u2013 Drumm singles, Marsh scores 1-0\n2\nnd\n\u2013 LIBERTY - Campos reached on a fielder's choice, Sorenson scores, 2-0\n6\nth\n- Mo ST \u2013 Golbert homers, 2-1\n7\nth\n\u2013 Mo ST \u2013 Cermenelli reached on a fielder's choice, Fyffe scores, 2-2\n7\nth\n\u2013 LIBERTY \u2013 Marsh doubles, Campos scores, 3-2\n8\nth\n\u2013 Mo ST \u2013 Bergman homers, Golbert scores, 4-3\nNotable Numbers\n- Missouri State outhit Liberty, 11-6. The Bears committed the game's only error.\n- Liberty left eight men on base. Missouri State left nine men on base.\n- Flames starting pitcher\nBen Blair\ndid not factor in the decision. The right-hander allowed one run on six hits over six innings. He struck out eight and did not walk a batter.\n- Reliever\nJosh Swink\ntakes the loss. The left-hander gave up three runs on five hits over 2 1/3 innings. He struck out three and walked one.\n- Tyler Ash, the third of four Missouri State relievers in the game, picks up the win. The reliever pitched a scoreless 1 1/3 innings, not yielding a hit. He struck out two and walked two.\n- Charlton earns his second save of the season. He retired three of the four batters he faced, striking out one and walking one.\n- Bears right-fielder Taeg Gollert collected three hits, including his third home run of the year. He had an RBI and scored twice.\n- Bergman's two-run home run in the eighth inning was the Missouri State catcher's seventh of the season.\nBeyond the Box Score\n- Today's game was the first meeting between Missouri State and Liberty on the baseball diamond in the programs' histories. In addition, the Bears were playing in their first-ever Conference USA game after joining the conference this fall.\n- The loss halts Liberty's winning streak at 10 games. The streak was the longest winning streak by a Flames team since an 11-game winning streak Feb. 19-March 8, 2022. It is also the longest by the Flames under head coach\nBradley LeCroy\n- Marsh extends his hitting streak to 13 games. It is one shy of the shortstop career-high of 14 games. He also has reached base in every game this season. With two hits, he leads the Flames with six multi-hit games.\nUp Next\nLiberty and Missouri State will meet in the middle game of their three-game, CUSA opening series tomorrow. The first pitch is scheduled for 2 p.m."
